WEBVTT

00:00:00.560 --> 00:00:09.280
Hi everyone, my name is Shel, a data analytics consultant based in Nairobi, Kenya.

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:14.000
Today I'm going to show you how you can quickly make your shiny apps mobile responsive.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.320
At the beginning of the year, I joined a team that had built an amazing app, but users were

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:21.040
finding it hard to maneuver it through their phones.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:26.559
I was required to make the app mobile responsive while making very minimal edits to the R code.

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:32.480
I took this as a challenge and within 2-3 weeks, we had the mobile shiny app ready and deployed.

00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:37.439
Apps are said to be mobile responsive if they are optimized to be functional

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:40.799
and aesthetically pleasing on devices of different sizes.

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:45.599
For this talk, I created a dummy shiny app that you can access via bit.ly slash mfano.

00:00:45.599 --> 00:00:49.040
You can also access it by scanning the QR code displayed.

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:51.360
This is the same app, but with a few differences,

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:54.400
depending on whether you view it on a laptop or mobile phone.

00:00:55.360 --> 00:00:59.520
The first thing you can do is to set the app such that the menu is collapsible.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:03.040
In shiny, by default, when collapsible is set to true,

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:06.639
the menu is collapsed and the screen size is 940 pixels or less.

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:10.959
Here, I used CSS and media queries to style the menu icon

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:14.639
and to reduce the font size of the tab names and tab background color.

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:20.160
CSS is used to style HTML elements and media queries enable web page content

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:23.360
to adapt to different screen sizes and resolutions.

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:25.360
Think of media queries as eval statements.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:29.199
For example, if the screen size is less than 480 pixels,

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:32.720
typical of mobile phones, convert the background color to pink

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:35.120
or the h1 font size to 8 pixels.

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:37.599
We use breakpoints with media queries to set points

00:01:37.599 --> 00:01:40.400
where websites adjust to the width of devices.

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:43.199
Next, you can choose to remove some objects

00:01:43.199 --> 00:01:45.680
so that they are not visible on some devices.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:50.320
In this example, we removed the icons and introduced a button on the mobile view.

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:54.000
You can do this by setting display as none in CSS.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.199
I also used media queries to edit the topography of the paragraphs for the mobile view.

00:01:59.199 --> 00:02:01.360
Shiny browser, a package by Dinatali,

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:05.680
lets you easily detect a user's web browser information in shiny.

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:08.880
One of the caveats is that the width and the height of the browser window

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:12.720
are only reported once when the detect function is initially called,

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:15.919
so you'd need to refresh the page to get the new dimensions.

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:19.759
You can use shiny browser to reduce the font size of different things

00:02:19.759 --> 00:02:22.479
such as plot titles, axis text and labels.

00:02:23.119 --> 00:02:25.279
You can have a function that generates your graph

00:02:25.279 --> 00:02:27.119
with an argument of type of device.

00:02:27.119 --> 00:02:28.880
For example, if your device is mobile,

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:31.839
we want the title to be of size 14, otherwise size 18.

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:35.759
Then on the UI, insert the detect function and on the server,

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:40.240
define a reactive element that detects the type of device based on the device's width

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:42.880
and use this as the graph's function argument.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.639
And this is what I did in the Kwanzaa tab.

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:51.360
The axis text size in the desktop view is a bit larger than that in the mobile view.

00:02:52.399 --> 00:02:56.160
You can use the same principle to change the orientation of the graph

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:57.839
as seen on the tattoo tab.

00:02:57.839 --> 00:03:00.000
On the mobile view, the chart is flipped.

00:03:01.039 --> 00:03:05.520
You can also choose to change the order in which objects appear in each tab.

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:08.639
And this is where CSS Grid and Flexbox come into play.

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:11.759
They both define how elements are displayed on a web page.

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:17.119
Lastly, one trick that is really helpful is inspecting the browser.

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:20.800
You can play around changing some aspects and seeing how things look.

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:25.199
It is also very important to see how your app looks on different devices.

00:03:25.199 --> 00:03:28.720
And here, you can ask your friends to send you a screenshot

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:31.600
of output displayed by myviewport.com

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:36.080
and add the screen size dimension in the devices section.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:41.119
Once you are happy with the result, copy the rules to your CSS file,

00:03:41.119 --> 00:03:42.880
refresh and rerun.

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:46.960
You can perfectly see the media queries in action on your browser.

00:03:47.839 --> 00:03:52.240
And that, my friends, is how you can have a very awesome and usable shiny app

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:55.600
that can easily be viewed via a laptop or a mobile phone.

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:57.839
Now, disclaimers.

00:03:57.839 --> 00:04:01.279
Number one, I worked on this project before I learned about

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:03.759
Bootstrap and BSLib, so please check them out.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:09.440
Two, I'm not a CSS pro yet, so I believe my code could be more efficient.

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:12.800
And honestly, with CSS, you just need to keep guessing values

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:15.520
till things work and undo when things get worse.

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:20.880
You can access my code via bit.ly slash mfano code.

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:23.679
If you are attending the conference physically and you're interested

00:04:23.679 --> 00:04:25.760
in hearing more about this project,

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:28.880
please look for me over lunch hour so that we can chat.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:33.279
Thank you.

